<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1913-07-22T22:36:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1913-07-22T22:36:00-05:00" n="1017" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1017">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/8113.</note>
                        <head ana="#head_untitled-inferred-from-preceding-sibling-head">[Untitled]</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Mexico</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1913-07-22T21:00:00-06:36">
                                    <hi rend="italic">July 22, 1913—9 p.m.</hi>
                                </date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>354. I did not attend the demonstration in honor of the Japanese Minister
                            today, as I feared it would be made the occasion of an anti-American
                            demonstration. One speech of a rather anti-American nature was made, but
                            with this exception no anti-American expression was allowed although the
                            demonstration was meant as one against the United States rather than as
                            a greeting to the new Japanese Minister. The police had strict orders to
                            immediately suppress any anti-American expression.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Nelson O’Shaughnessy</hi>.</signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>